Mathieu   ‘Matthew’. Compare   Masse   5 and   Maze   3.","French (<b>Macé</b>): habitational name from Macé or La Ferté-Macé in Orne, the former so named from Gallo-Roman <i>Macciacum</i> (from the personal name <i>Maccius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>), the latter from the personal name <i>Macé</i> (see 2 above)."]},{"name":"Massie","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeen): variant of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Marsee","meanings":["English: altered form of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Massee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Germain.","Possibly an altered form of English   Massey  .","French (<b>Massée</b>): from the feminine form of <b>Massé</b> (see   Masse  ). This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Massa","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Antonio, Silvio, Annamarie, Biagio, Caesar, Carmela, Dante, Elisabetta, Ennio.","Italian: habitational name from any of various places called Massa, for example Massa Lubrense or Massa di Somma, both in Naples province, or Masse d'Albe in Aquila, all named from medieval Latin <i>massa</i> ‘farm, estate’ (from Latin <i>massa</i> ‘mass, lump, pile’, Greek <i>maza</i>). This surname is also found in southern France (see   Massey   5)."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Macey","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  .","Americanized form of Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Macej</b> or <b>Mačej</b> and Polish   Maciej  , derivatives of the Latin personal name <i>Matthaeus</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Masey","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Macy","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs John Massey was born about 1263, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with John Massey. She died about 1300, in her hometown, at the age of 39, and was buried in Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1263–about 1300":"umbes 1263–umbes 1300","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1263–1300":"1263–1300","1300":"1300","1286":"1286","1263":"1263","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1286":"umbes 1286","about 1263":"umbes 1263","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Charfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Charfield, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1263–about 1300":"noin 1263–noin 1300","1263–Male":"1263–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1263–1300":"1263–1300","1300":"1300","1286":"1286","1263"